  36. ‌and location =

  41. ‌and stack_location =
  42.     Local of int
  43.   | Incoming of int
  44.   | Outgoing of int
  45.   | Domainstate of int

  47. (* The [stack_location] describes the location of pseudo-registers
  48.    that reside in memory.
  49. - [Local] is a local variable or spilled register residing in the stack frame
  50.    of the current function
  51. - [Incoming] is a function parameter that was passed on the stack.
  52.    This is the callee's view: the location is just above the callee's
  53.    stack frame, in the caller's stack frame.
  54. - [Outgoing] is a function call argument that is passed on the stack.
  55.    This is the caller's view: the location is at the bottom of the
  56.    caller's stack frame.
  57. - [Domainstate] is a function call argument that is passed not on stack
  58.    but in the [extra_params] section of the domain state
  59.    (see file [../runtime/caml/domain_state.*]).  Unlike arguments passed
  60.    on stack, arguments passed via the domain state are compatible with
  61.    tail calls.  However, domain state locations are shared between
  62.    all functions that run in a given domain, hence they are not preserved
  63.    by function calls or thread context switches.  The caller stores
  64.    arguments in the domain state immediately before the call, and the
  65.    first thing the callee does is copy them to registers or [Local]
  66.    stack locations.  Neither GC nor thread context switches can occur
  67.    between these two times. *)
